text: As an adopted Ethiopian boy in America I am surrounded by American people But I kept my Ethiopian language and culture so close Now I am grown up and have my own apartment and unfortunately here in America your neighbor usually complains when you open laud music So I played Dishta Gina laud on the speaker dancing and singing at the same time So two white American neighbors showed up at my door I told them right away that I was sorry and that I will turn the volume down Their answer oh no we dont you to turn it down we just want to know the name of the song I invited them into my apartment and showed them the whole music video and they start dancing with me Just wanted to say THE POWER OF OUR ETHIOPIAN CULTURE
original: As an adopted Ethiopian boy in America, I am surrounded by American people. But I kept my Ethiopian language and culture so close. Now, I am grown up and have my own apartment and unfortunately here in America your neighbor usually complains when you open laud music. So, I played Dishta Gina laud on the speaker dancing and singing at the same time. So, two white American neighbors showed up at my door. I told them right away that I was sorry and that I will turn the volume down. Their answer, "oh no we don't you to turn it down, we just want to know the name of the song." I invited them into my apartment and showed them the whole music video, and they start dancing with me. Just wanted to say.... THE POWER OF OUR ETHIOPIAN CULTURE!

And then he says the following verses in Amharic and translated as follows:
Me and Adam( my father)
You and Eve (my bone)--he points his index finger towards his ribs[ reference to the Bible].
I came naked to this world and leave with nothing.
There is no best Ethnic group amongst ourselves.. 
Where does this Evil came from, we are all one.
Look up the sky and appreciate its beauty.
It is here on Earth that "We do not have LOVE".
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
He does not Sanctify you based on your Ethnicity(Besu Fit sitqom zer ayatsediq-Amharic).

original:
Dear Non Ethiopian Listeners,
I am amazed by your deep interest in Ethiopian music and for that I applaud you. In my opinion, the song went viral because of the message and the openness of TARIKU about his personal life on live TV interview. Tariku was born and grown up in the rural part of southern Ethiopia. He served in the military and fought a war in the North. Life was challenging for him when he was in the capital Addis Ababa. He worked as a day laborer and was living homeless life in the streets. Lastly, he decided to go back to his place of birth to break from the hustle and bustle of Addis Ababa . But the challenge he faced was that his people disowned him because of his gangster look with the long dread hair. He then went to local church and prayed to GOD to reveal his talent and make him somebody. Now he lives in the jungle as a farmer. He is the father of 5 kids. The meaning of his father's name [Gankisi] is "To break bad habits." He is happy with his life and never complains. He is full of positive energy and exerts this magnetic power in to the crowd with laughter.

DISHTA GHINE means New Year in "ARI" language. It is an Afro -Asiatic > Omotic>South language.
He begins the song by calling all the months and asking everybody to forgive their wrong doings and hope the New Year to brings happiness. And then he says the following verses in Amharic and translated as follows:

Me and Adam( my father)
You and Eve (my bone)--he points his index finger towards his ribs[ reference to the Bible].
I came naked to this world and leave with nothing.
There is no best Ethnic group/race amongst ourselves.. 
Where does this Evil came from, we are all one.
Look up the sky, no one washes it or cleans it but it is amazingly beautiful.
It is here on Earth that "We do not have LOVE".
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race.
You came from there, I came from there, We all came from there, We are all one(This is where he grasps his chest)
We are scattered all over the world after the fall of Babylon from God's grace.
To this day, we do not have a true love. no matter how we sing about it.
What should we do ?
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race./2/

It is a dazzling, mesmerizing, inspirational, and spiritual song full of positivity that reminds everybody that "We are created in the image of GOD.

Solomon Tadesse
Boston, Massachusetts

text: Amazigh people are native Africans They originated around Ancient Egypt and Lybia As a cyclical cultural continuity many people in the Sahara region have ancient Historical contacts Even with this diverse sparse land People have traded traveled and influenced one an other since antiquity In ancient time transSaharan traders used to navigate from the tip of Somaliland up to the riff atlas mountain Many Western Historians now a days like to to ignore this fact There was a trade route named Neqada Behir which traders from Mediterranean Red sea and Atlantic ocean used to meet Still the significant impact and the clear trace they made is undeniable Ps It is better if you dont use the name Berber to refer your self The more acceptable term should be Amazigh Imazighen or any of your tribe name The term BerberBarabarian is derogatory word given to them by Europeans
original:
Amazigh people are native Africans. They originated around Ancient Egypt and Lybia. As a cyclical cultural continuity, many people in the Sahara region have ancient Historical contacts. Even with this diverse sparse land. People have traded / traveled and influenced one an other since antiquity. In ancient time trans-Saharan traders used to navigate from the tip of Somali-land up to the riff atlas mountain. Many Western Historians now a days like to to ignore this fact, There was a trade route named " Neqada Behir ", which traders from Mediterranean, Red sea and Atlantic ocean used to meet. Still the significant impact and the clear trace they made is un-deniable.

P.s. It is better if you don't use the name "Berber" to refer your self. The more acceptable term should be Amazigh / Imazighen or any of your tribe name. The term Berber/Barabarian is derogatory word given to them by Europeans.

These are the lyrics.
Me and Adam( my father)
You and Eve (my bone)--he points his index finger towards his ribs[ reference to the Bible].
I came naked to this world and leave with nothing.
There is no best Ethnic group/race amongst ourselves.. 
Where does this Evil came from, we are all one.
Look up the sky, no one washes it or cleans it but it is amazingly beautiful.
It is here on Earth that "We do not have LOVE".
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race.
You came from there, I came from there, We all came from there, We are all one(This is where he grasps his chest)
We are scattered all over the world after the fall of Babylon from God's grace.
To this day, we do not have a true love. no matter how we sing about it.
What should we do ?
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.

original:
I don't know what he says in the Ari language, but in Amharic he says:
"I brought nothing down and I don't take anything back up. Who called the pure seed a chaff? Adam my brother, me and Adam my one father. You and Eve my one bone. It's our deed on earth we have to answer to. When we stand before Him, seed (race) doesn't make you righteous. No one washes her, no one sweeps her, but look at the sky how beautiful she is. Woe earth woe. I'm from you, you're from me, but love is lost. You are from there (above), I am from there. Babylon dispersed us, and until this day we lost true love; nothing to sing, nothing to chant. What's better for us now?" The song fades out as he repeats it.

At 01:16
"Dishta Gina,  Dishta Gina;
Gail babo, a Dishta Gina
Baarger babo, a Dishta Gina
Sida babo, irar Dishta Gina
Seiti babo, irar Dishta Gina
Teyye babo, irar Dishta Gina
Baka babo, irar Dishta Gina
Huba babo, hura Dishta Gine
Laide babo, hura Dishta Gine
Woze babo, hibaa goyse akka
Arit Dishta Gine
Arit Dishta Gine" 
I'D REALLY LOVE to KNOW WHAT MEANS.

original:
He says the following verses in Amharic and translated as follows:
Me and Adam( my father)
You and Eve (my bone)--he points his index finger towards his ribs[ reference to the Bible].
I came naked to this world and leave with nothing.
There is no best Ethnic group amongst ourselves.. 
Where does this Evil came from, we are all one.
Look up the sky and appreciate its beauty.
It is here on Earth that "We do not have LOVE".
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
He does not Sanctify you based on your Ethnicity(Besu Fit sitqom zer ayatsediq-Amharic).
You came from there, I came from there, We all came from there, We are all one(This is where he grasps his chest)
In light of the current ethnic cleansing and killing in Ethiopia, such a dazzling, mesmerizing, inspirational,  and spiritual song full of positivity that reminds everybody that "We are created in the image of GOD"  is of paramount importance for reconciliation.

Â @cubadebesai1356Â  I got this from another comment of a guy named Solomon the lyrics are at the bottom the song is using 2 languages and the amharic language part of the song is below for you, -------Tariku the singer was born and grown up in the rural part of southern Ethiopia. He served in the military and fought a war in the North. Life was challenging for him when he was in the capital Addis Ababa. He worked as a day laborer and was living homeless life in the streets. Lastly, he decided to go back to his place of birth to break from the hustle and bustle of Addis Ababa . But the challenge he faced was that his people disowned him because of his gangster look with the long dread hair. He then went to local church and prayed to GOD to reveal his talent and make him somebody. Now he lives in the jungle as a farmer. He is the father of 5 kids. The meaning of his father's name [Gankisi] is "To break bad habits." He is happy with his life and never complains. He is full of positive energy and exerts this magnetic power in to the crowd with laughter.

DISHTA GHINE means New Year in "ARI" language. It is an Afro -Asiatic > Omotic>South language.
He begins the song by calling all the months and asking everybody to forgive their wrong doings and hope the New Year to brings happiness. And then he says the following verses in Amharic and translated as follows:

Me and Adam( my father)
You and Eve (my bone)--he points his index finger towards his ribs[ reference to the Bible].
I came naked to this world and leave with nothing.
There is no best Ethnic group/race amongst ourselves.. 
Where does this Evil came from, we are all one.
Look up the sky, no one washes it or cleans it but it is amazingly beautiful.
It is here on Earth that "We do not have LOVE".
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race.
You came from there, I came from there, We all came from there, We are all one(This is where he grasps his chest)
We are scattered all over the world after the fall of Babylon from God's grace.
To this day, we do not have a true love. no matter how we sing about it.
What should we do ?
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.

You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race./2/

I don't know what he says in the Ari language, but in Amharic he says:
"I brought nothing down and I don't take anything back up. Who called the pure seed a chaff? Adam my brother, me and Adam my one father. You and Eve my one bone. It's our deed on earth we have to answer to. When we stand before Him, seed (race) doesn't make you righteous. No one washes her, no one sweeps her, but look at the sky how beautiful she is. Woe earth woe. I'm from you, you're from me, but love is lost. You are from there (above), I am from there. Babylon dispersed us, and until this day we lost true love; nothing to sing, nothing to chant. What's better for us now?" The song fades out as he repeats it.

At 01:16

I don't know what he says in the Ari language, but in Amharic he says:
"I brought nothing down and I don't take anything back up. Who decided the pure seed and the chaff? Adam my brother, me and Adam my one father. You and Eve my one bone. It's what we do on earth we have to answer for. When we stand before Him, seed (race) doesn't make you righteous. No one washes her, no one sweeps her, but look at the sky how beautiful she is. Woe earth woe. I'm from you, you're from me, but love is lost. You are from there (above), I am from there. Babylon dispersed us, and until this day we lost true love; nothing to sing, nothing to chant. What's better for us now?" The song fades out as he repeats it.

original:
Dear Non Ethiopian Listeners,
I am amazed by your deep interest in Ethiopian music and for that I applaud you. In my opinion, the song went viral because of the message and the openness of TARIKU about his personal life on live TV interview. Tariku was born and grown up in the rural part of southern Ethiopia. He served in the military and fought a war in the North. Life was challenging for him when he was in the capital Addis Ababa. He worked as a day laborer and was living homeless life in the streets. Lastly, he decided to go back to his place of birth to break from the hustle and bustle of Addis Ababa . But the challenge he faced was that his people disowned him because of his gangster look with the long dread hair. He then went to local church and prayed to GOD to reveal his talent and make him somebody. Now he lives in the jungle as a farmer. He is the father of 5 kids. The meaning of his father's name [Gankisi] is "To break bad habits." He is happy with his life and never complains. He is full of positive energy and exerts this magnetic power in to the crowd with laughter.

DISHTA GHINE means New Year in "ARI" language. It is an Afro -Asiatic > Omotic>South language.
He begins the song by calling all the months and asking everybody to forgive their wrong doings and hope the New Year to brings happiness. And then he says the following verses in Amharic and translated as follows:

Me and Adam( my father)
You and Eve (my bone)--he points his index finger towards his ribs[ reference to the Bible].
I came naked to this world and leave with nothing.
There is no best Ethnic group/race amongst ourselves.. 
Where does this Evil came from, we are all one.
Look up the sky, no one washes it or cleans it but it is amazingly beautiful.
It is here on Earth that "We do not have LOVE".
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.
You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race.
You came from there, I came from there, We all came from there, We are all one(This is where he grasps his chest)
We are scattered all over the world after the fall of Babylon from God's grace.
To this day, we do not have a true love. no matter how we sing about it.
What should we do ?
GOD judges you for what you did on earth.

You do not get salvation before God  based on your Ethnicity/race./2/

It is a dazzling, mesmerizing, inspirational, and spiritual song full of positivity that reminds everybody that "We are created in the image of GOD.

Solomon Tadesse
Boston, Massachusetts
